A SCOTS <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Family" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Family" target="_blank">family</a> have revealed how they were five minutes from certain death in the Nepal earthquakeDavid Knox was on holiday with his wife Aileen and fouryearold daughter Jess when they found themselves at the centre of the 78 magnitude tremorThey had been visiting the temples in the iconic Durbur Square in Patan when they decided to make a trip to a nearby museum on SaturdayFive <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/60_Minutes" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/60_Minutes" target="_blank">minutes</a> later the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Earthquake" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Earthquake" target="_blank">earthquake</a> struck and they could only watch as the temples in the square crashed to the ground  killing many of those insideTheir holiday of a lifetime quickly turned into a nightmare with their plans to return home to Scotland the following day scuppered amidst all the chaosIn a phone call from the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/British_people" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/British_people" target="_blank">British</a> Embassy in Kathmandu48yearold David a journalist with the Border Telegraph in Galashiels said âWe were in Patan which is the city next to Kathmandu when the <a href="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Earthquake" title="http://dbpedia.org/resource/Earthquake" target="_blank">earthquake</a> happenedâWe had been on the temples in Durbur Square with my little girl Jess getting some photographs taken on the last day of our holidaysâWe decided to pop over to a nearby museum paid our money to get in and were just climbing the stairs when the craziest thing ever happened âWe were getting thrown from side to side wall to wallâWe looked out the window across to the square and watched as the temples crashed to the groundâIt was devastation after thatâWe took refuge in some gardens for about four to five hours with afte